Check whether sampling variance of lnCVR is sensitive for asuumption on correlation

Check whether sampling variance calculated assuming corelation is/is not different between groups.

# confirm high correlation between two ways in calculating variance of lnCVR
cor.test(ES.epistasis$lnCVR.sv.corF, ES.epistasis$lnCVR.sv.corT)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  ES.epistasis$lnCVR.sv.corF and ES.epistasis$lnCVR.sv.corT
## t = 22971, df = 1190, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9999987 0.9999990
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9999989

Draw funnel plot for each effect sizes

First, funnel plot should be made to check odd studies (i.e. very large/small effect size and large error variance)

Drop data with extremely high Precision

In difference between cross direction, funnel plot showed extremely high/low Precision in effect sizes (lnRR comparing mean phenotype between reciprocal hybrids), which prevents meta-analysis.
This could be due to low variation resulting from inbred strain, but not error in typing.
Hence, I drop these two effect sizes

# Difference in means between cross directions: lnRR
regtest(x = ES.recip.2$lnRR.recip.es, vi = ES.recip.2$lnRR.recip.sv,
        predictor = "vi")
